X and Y are independent normal random variables with X ~ N(5, 16) and Y ~ N(6, 9). The goal is to find P(X > Y) = P(X - Y > 0).

Since X and Y are independent, the difference X - Y follows a normal distribution. The mean of X - Y is E[X] - E[Y] = 5 - 6 = -1. The variance of X - Y is Var(X) + Var(Y) = 16 + 9 = 25, so the standard deviation is √25 = 5. Thus, X - Y ~ N(-1, 25).

P(X - Y > 0) is the probability that a normal random variable with mean -1 and standard deviation 5 exceeds 0. Standardizing this, the z-score is (0 - (-1)) / 5 = 1/5 = 0.2. Therefore, P(X - Y > 0) = P(Z > 0.2) for a standard normal variable Z.

Using the standard normal distribution, P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - P(Z < 0.2). The cumulative probability P(Z < 0.2) is approximately 0.5793, so P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - 0.5793 = 0.4207. Rounded to three decimal places, this is 0.421.

