 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem requires finding the approximate probability \(P(52.761 \leq \bar{X} \leq 54.453)\) for the sample mean \(\bar{X}\) of a random sample of size \(n = 47\) from a population with mean \(\mu = 54.030\) and standard deviation \(\sigma = 5.8\).

Given the sample size \(n = 47 > 30\), the Central Limit Theorem applies, and the sampling distribution of \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normal with mean \(\mu = 54.030\) and standard error \(\sigma / \sqrt{n} = 5.8 / \sqrt{47}\).

The standard error is calculated as:
\[
\sqrt{47} \approx 6.8556546, \quad \text{so} \quad \sigma / \sqrt{n} = 5.8 / 6.8556546 \approx 0.845822.
\]

The z-scores for the bounds are:
- Lower bound: \(z_{\text{lower}} = (52.761 - 54.030) / 0.845822 = (-1.269) / 0.845822 \approx -1.4995\)
- Upper bound: \(z_{\text{upper}} = (54.453 - 54.030) / 0.845822 = 0.423 / 0.845822 \approx 0.4998\)

The probability \(P(-1.4995 \leq Z \leq 0.4998)\) for a standard normal variable \(Z\) is found using the cumulative distribution function (CDF):
\[
P(Z \leq 0.4998) \approx 0.6913896, \quad P(Z \leq -1.4995) \approx 0.0668720.
\]
Thus,
\[
P(52.761 \leq \bar{X} \leq 54.453) = P(Z \leq 0.4998) - P(Z \leq -1.4995) \approx 0.6913896 - 0.0668720 = 0.6245176.
\]

