Problem: The positron has charge $+e$ and mass equal to the electron mass. Calculate in electronvolts the ground-state energy of positronium-an "atom" that consists of a positron and an electron. The unit of the answer should be $\mathrm{eV}$.
Solution: The ground-state energy of positronium is derived from the hydrogen atom ground-state energy, which is -13.6 eV. In positronium, both the electron and positron have the same mass, resulting in a reduced mass that is half of the electron mass. The ground-state energy scales with the reduced mass, so for positronium, it is half of the hydrogen value. Thus, the energy is -13.6 eV divided by 2, which equals -6.8 eV. This value is rounded to a reasonable number of significant figures based on the input.

